DOMAIN_OVERVIEW:

This domain encompasses both general philosophical theories of autonomy and their
specific applications to workplace contexts. The philosophical literature on autonomy
divides into several major traditions: (1) Kantian accounts emphasizing rational
self-legislation and moral autonomy (Kant, Korsgaard); (2) hierarchical mesh theories
focusing on identification with desires (Frankfurt, Dworkin); (3) reasons-responsiveness
accounts examining the quality of deliberative mechanisms (Fischer & Ravizza, Wolf);
(4) relational autonomy approaches emphasizing social constitution of agency (Mackenzie
& Stoljar, Friedman, Westlund); and (5) competency-based accounts stressing skills and
capacities (Benson, Meyers).

The workplace-specific literature examines how these general theories apply to contexts
of employment, labor, and organizational life. Key debates include: whether workplace
democracy is required by autonomy (Anderson, Dahl, Frega et al.); what makes work
meaningful (Veltman, Schwartz, Cholbi); how hierarchical authority affects worker
autonomy (Herzog, Chi Kwok); and whether AI/automation threatens meaningful work
(Bankins & Formosa). Recent work increasingly integrates empirical findings about
workplace conditions with normative philosophical frameworks.

RELEVANCE_TO_PROJECT:

This domain provides foundational philosophical frameworks for understanding autonomy
that any empirical research on workplace autonomy must engage with. The tension between
sophisticated philosophical accounts of autonomy (identification, reasons-responsiveness,
relational constitution) and operationalizable empirical measures is central to the
research project. The workplace-specific literature directly addresses how AI and
organizational structures affect worker autonomy, making it essential for situating
empirical findings within normative debates about what autonomy requires and why it
matters for human flourishing.

RECENT_DEVELOPMENTS:

The last five years (2020-2025) have seen significant developments in three areas:
(1) increased philosophical attention to AI's impact on autonomy and meaningful work,
with papers examining how automation affects worker agency; (2) renewed interest in
workplace democracy and economic justice, particularly post-COVID considerations of
remote work and worker control; (3) sophisticated work on relational autonomy that
challenges traditional individualistic conceptions while maintaining normative force.

NOTABLE_GAPS:

While there is extensive general autonomy theory and growing workplace philosophy
literature, there remains limited philosophical work directly bridging these domains -
particularly on how specific workplace conditions (surveillance, algorithmic management,
automation) affect the conditions for autonomy as understood in sophisticated
philosophical frameworks. Few papers operationalize philosophical concepts like
"reasons-responsiveness" or "identification" for empirical testing in workplace contexts.

SYNTHESIS_GUIDANCE:

For synthesis, prioritize: (1) Frankfurt (1971) and Dworkin (1988) as foundational
hierarchical accounts; (2) Mackenzie & Stoljar (2000) as the key relational autonomy
collection; (3) Christman's SEP article and his 2009 book for contemporary procedural
accounts; (4) Anderson (2017) and Veltman (2016) for workplace applications; (5) Bankins
& Formosa (2023) for recent AI/meaningful work integration. The review should emphasize
how workplace conditions enable or undermine the social and psychological conditions
these theories identify as necessary for autonomy.

KEY_POSITIONS:
- Kantian moral autonomy: 3 papers - Rational self-legislation and dignity
- Hierarchical mesh theories: 4 papers - Identification and second-order desires
- Reasons-responsiveness: 3 papers - Quality of deliberative mechanisms
- Relational autonomy: 8 papers - Social constitution and feminist critiques
- Workplace democracy: 6 papers - Democratic governance of firms
- Meaningful work: 5 papers - Conditions for work to support flourishing
- AI and automation ethics: 3 papers - Technology's impact on agency and meaning
- Capabilities approaches: 2 papers - Functionings and substantive freedoms
- Conceptual engineering: 2 papers - Revising and improving concepts
====================================================================
